  surprises / policy-relevant observations:
    1. judiciary.gov.zm is effectively a thin redirect shell. GET / 30x's to judiciaryzambia.com, the sitemap on .gov.zm lists only .com URLs, and the two origins serve a byte-identical robots.txt. For all practical purposes the corpus target is judiciaryzambia.com. The .gov.zm host is the politically canonical name (government TLD) but the operational host is the .com. Phase 3 source lock should be updated to reflect this: "Judiciary of Zambia — judiciary.gov.zm (redirects to and content hosted on judiciaryzambia.com)".
    2. The nav is live JavaScript/WordPress but the links are plain server-rendered anchors, so no JS execution is required to walk the category archives. scripts/fetch_one.py is sufficient for the listing walk.
    3. WordPress category archives at /category/resources/decisions/<court>-decisions/ are paginated (/page/N/) by default in WordPress. Pagination cost for Phase 3 is cheap (single PDF target) but for Phase 4 bulk we will need to know how many pages deep Supreme Court goes; that is a Phase 4 concern, not a J-POL-1 concern.
    4. PDF filenames on .com contain rich metadata (citation-style prefix, parties, date, coram). This will make Phase 3 target selection and Phase 4 bulk cataloguing much easier than the parliament.gov.zm Drupal 7 file naming.
    5. A wp-json REST API is advertised in the Link header. Using it would be faster and more structured than HTML scraping, but it's new surface area with its own rate-limit/quota posture; recommend NOT adopting it in Phase 3 (stay on HTML + direct PDF), reconsider for Phase 4 bulk.
    6. judiciaryzambia.com is a .com, not a Zambian-government TLD. That is worth naming explicitly — the authoritativeness argument rests on the site being operated by the Judiciary of Zambia in fact, which is corroborated by the title tag, the robots.txt identity with .gov.zm, and the 30x redirect from .gov.zm. Provenance records for Phase 3 PDFs should capture BOTH the .gov.zm canonical name and the .com operational URL (e.g. as source_url=.com and a notes entry or a second provenance field for the canonical host) so that the chain of trust to the government host is preserved in the record.
    7. Cross-domain sitemap is an interesting AI-training-posture quirk: the byte-identical robots.txt means a reservation on .com would automatically propagate to .gov.zm (and vice versa), because whichever admin edits the file edits both. Good for us — one file to watch.

